review_blob: Just what I want from an IPA--clear golden with a lacy white head. Chewy mouthfeel. Piney and floral aroma that leads you to a slightly sweet, appropriately bitter banquet of flavors--grapefruit, caramel, pine, toffee...A real winner.
beer_name: NoDa Hop, Drop n Roll IPA

review_blob: Nice dark, cloudy amber appearance. Sweet and grapefruity nose. Taste is pretty sweet, a bit of caramel, and a nice dry bitterness at the end.

Medium brown, crystal clear, with a decent sized head. Slightly nutty, caramel aroma. Flavor is heavy on caramel, with some roasted, almost burnt notes. Only slightly sweet, with a terribly watery mouthfeel. Not at all a decent representative of the style.

Fairly fruity nose, with some spice--coriander, white pepper, cloves--and  a bit musty. Orange with a good deal of sediment and not much of a head. Flavor is rather sweet, a good bit of bubble gum and clove, with quite a bitter end. Nice, very much not what Im used to from Lagunitas. Not an exemplar of the style, but good nonetheless.
beer_name: Lagunitas Were Only In It For The Money

review_blob: Hazy, honey/amber colored with a relatively small off-white head. Nose is quite sweet, with some citrus notes as well as peaches and sugar. Flavor is sweet, with a good dose of citric hops backing that up. Notes of grass and a nice astringency in the finish.

(On cask, dryhopped, at Clybourn) Clear, and in fact golden, with basically no head. Light nose, fairly bitter,notable corn and veggie aromas. Flavor is relatively bitter, rather astringent, and soapy, with hints of orange and apricots. Overall thin, and not particularly pleasant.

On cask. Appropriately hazy, orange/yellow with a small white head. Nose is slightly citric, a bit musty, somewhat sweet. Flavor leans toward oranges and apricots, medium bitter, not too sweet. Excellent soft, full mouthfeel.
beer_name: Rock Bottom Orland Park American Dream Ale

review_blob: (Tasted 6/08, bottled 2005) Clear, with a dark straw color and good-sized white head of smallish bubbles. Nose is initially sour enough to curl the hairs in the back of your nose, but lightens up after a few moments to allow some very nice bready undertones through, not to mention ample notes of musty hay and lemons, as well as some spice--oregano perhaps. Flavor is not too brutally sour. Lots of green grass in there, some lemons, rye, grapes, and more hay. A wonderful refreshing drop for a hot summers evening.

Dark, clear copper, with a smallish white head. Nose is rather sweet, like toffee or caramel, hints of honey. Though this is a fairly fresh bottle, it has all the mellow sweetness and none of the harsh bitter notes of a fresh barleywine. Good deal of honey and caramel in taste, with bits of tobacco and some plums. A dry, almondy bitterness puts it in balance. Slightly slick mouthfeel, but overall soft and pleasant.

Dark tan, a bit hazy, with a smallish white head. Nose is of honey and cereal. Flavor has a smallish shot of citric hops, and a nice bit of  honey. Surprisingly well-crafted product from a big regional brewer.

Clear, dark ruddy brown with a short lived tan head. Aroma has a bit of melanoidy malt,  slightly bitter and nutty. Taste is somewhat sweet, with some prunes, peanuts, and chocolate. A light bitter snap at the end. Solid session brew on the sweeter end of the spectrum.
Clear golden, with a short lived, white head. Disappointingly one-dimensional--bitter, dry, and astringent.

Hazy reddish brown, with a robust off-white head. Nose is initially quite astringent, bitter, with a lot of fresh-cut grass, giving way to caramel, walnuts, and a bit of alcohol. Flavor is quite sweet, with oranges and a powerful dry bitterness. Great, full, soft mouthfeel.

Deep red-orange, cloudy, with a huge off-white head. Light, sweet nose, with touches of vanilla and walnuts. Flavor is fairly sweet, a bit astringent, quite bitter, with some touches of tobacco, almonds and walnuts.

Clear dark yellow with a god sized white head. Nose is somewhat sweet, with hints of citrusy hops. Flavor is initially quite tart, belying the wheat, and gives way to a strong, dry, and relatively unexciting bitterness. Neither satisfying as a big wheat or as a hop monster.

Cloudy honey-colored with a smallish white head. Nose is quite bitter, with lots of citrus, a touch of caramel. Flavor is quite sweet, backed up by a dry, nutty bitterness. Plenty of grapefruit, almonds, and touches of vanilla and cake.
beer_name: Moylans Hopsickle Imperial India Pale Ale

review_blob: Cloudy, dark red-brown with a small off white head. Sweet nose with touches of carob and caramel, a bit of plum. Pleasant, fruity flavor with some nice chocolatey notes. Quite sweet--might take well to a bit of age.

Clear, dark yellow, with a big, rocky white head. Nose is odd, off, with plastic/band-aid aromas dominating, some sweetness under there as well. Flavor is none too pleasant either, with plenty of cooked vegetable notes--squash, cabbage--and strong, almondy bitterness.

Dark, cloudy red-brown, with a small off-white head that gives up the ghost pretty quick. Nose is fairly sweet, with some chocolate, plums, some cinnamon. Flavor is sugary-sweet, with some nice, subdued spicy notes (black pepper, coriander), a solid nutty bitterness, more plums or prunes. .
beer_name: Dark Horse Scotty Karate Scotch Ale

review_blob: Hazy, dark amber, with a nice, rocky off-white head. Nose is aggressively bitter, somewhat musty, with a bit of cheese. Dry flavor, quite bitter, musty, not much of interest going on there.

Clear but dark ruddy copper, with a good sized, lasting off white head. Nose is fairly sweet with caramel notes, and a strong piney, grassy hop profile. Flavor is quite sweet, with a bit of tobacco, plums, raisins. Quite bitter, but nicely balanced. Good, creamy mouthfeel.

Dark red/brown, almost opaque, with a medium sized brown head that doesnt last long. Nose is complicated--salty, fairly sweet, a bit of alcohol, some carob and caramel, and slight tannic notes. Flavor is quite sweet, with a nice banana overtone, marked bitterness, and an earthy aftertaste. Slightly tart, almost oaky hints in there, as well as cherries and prunes. Mouthfeel is a bit chalky, and its overcarbonated right now. Might do well to get a bit of age on this one.

Clear copper, with a sizzling, short-lived white head. OK nose, slightly sweet with a slight bit of kumquat and some musty grain. Decent flavor, somewhat orangey, a bit floral, medium bitterness. Surprisingly good coming from Abita.

Clear copper, with a smallish white head that leaves some OK lace. Aroma is fairly sweet, a bit musty, a bit peanut-buttery, with some slightly spicy notes. Fairly sweet in flavor, and very bitter, with some grassy hop undertones. And I cant shake this sense of peanut butter--its not a bad thing, just unusual. Very good creamy mouthfeel.

Hazy, honey-colored, with a large white head. Beautiful nose, with orange, pine, fresh cut grass, some caramel notes. A bit dryer than it perhaps should be--quite bitter, with a lot of pine and citrus, touches of bready malts.

Dark brown, clear, with a good sized tan head. Nose is somewhat spicy, with a bit of licorice, some black pepper, slightly sweet, and includes some metallic notes. Rather sweet, bready flavor with a good deal of bitterness, some rye notes, molasses. Very nice, pillowy mouthfeel.

Clear copper with a small white head. Nose is a bit harsh, with metallic bananas and some fusel alcohol. Rather sweet in flavor, with lots of banana. Quite bitter, a bit salty. Not criminally bad, perhaps, but hardly very good.

Clear, very light yellow, with a short-lived but large white head. Nose has a decent bit of grassy hops, some lemon, but also some corn and metallic notes. Basic euro-lager flavor, though a bit sweeter than the norm. Some noble hops, medium bitter with very clean finish, a light malty body.

Rather weak nose--slightly sweet, some carob, black tea, orange, a hint of coffee. Practically no head, with a red/brown body. Flavor is quite nice, though it could be more robust. Its fairly sweet, with a bit of chocolate, some dry bitterness, and some orange or apricot notes.

Pretty bad gusher. After the head subsided, Im left with a short pour of a dark brown beer with a nicely lacing tan head. Aroma is quite sweet, with a lot of chocolate and carob, some walnut, soil, and alcohol. Flavor is somewhat musty, mildly sweet, and dominated by a dry, almond bitterness. Good beer, better cause.
beer_name: Bison Reunion - A Beer For Hope (2007)

review_blob: From a fresh growler. Clear copper, barely any head. Not the greatest nose--very light, a bit of grassy hops, but also some unpleasant vegetal notes. Fortunately, not much of that vegetal nature comes through in the flavor, which is overall lightly sweet, with some bready notes, and barely any hop presence beside a wee bit of fresh cut grass. The educational mantra behind deciding to make this batch 500 is a neat idea, but Im not sure this is a style that deserves much hype.

On tap, from the brewpub. Opaque black, small whitish head. Interesting nose--quite sweet, with some tannic notes, chocolate, raspberry, and a hint of soy. Flavor is quite sweet, a bit chocolatey, medium bitter, with a good dose of slightly smokey, boozey bourbon flavors. Slightly chalky, but overall very pleasant.

Hazy copper, with a pillowy white head. Nose is wonderful--lots of resiny, piney hops, and a ton of violet/floral notes, but not overly bitter. Reminds me a lot of draft Dreadnaught in its prime. The flavor is quite dry, and very bitter, with some violets and grapefruit. All those hops could really use a bit more gravity for some balance.

Hazy red/brown, with a pillowy off-white head. Nose is quite tangy, with light beech smoke, a bit of bitter almonds. Flavor is lightly sweet, with a very nice light smokiness that lingers on the palate, some nutty notes as well.

Dark amber, with a smallish white head that leaves a good lace. Nose is totally hops--resiny pine, grapefruit rind, and a bit of cannabis. Flavor is similarly hop dominated--crazy amounts of bitter citrus, a touch of fresh-cut grass, but its balanced pretty nicely by a toffeeish malt backbone.

An almost still, dark brown beer, this has a profoundly oaky nose, with the tannic and uric notes I associate with oak barrel aging over a rather sweet, cookie-like nose. The flavor is quite sweet and a bit chocolatey, almost like a tootsie role. There is certainly a good dose of oak there, but its not offensively tannic, and there are a number of pleasant hints in there as well of tobacco, almonds, and cherry wood smoke. Fantastic.

Hazy, straw colored, with a smallish white head. Nose is sweet, with some grassy hop notes, some honey, and a bit of citric hop aroma that seems out of place. Way too bitter for the style. Rather musty, with some grass and earth notes in there, as well as some very faint hints of orange. Not very sweet. Very much off-style, but a decent beer nonetheless

Straw colored, clear, with a decent sized white head. Fairly sweet nose with a bit of caramel, lots of resiny hops, with grapefruit and pine, some apricot. Extremely bitter--almost like a spoiled walnut. Doesnt seem to be enough sweetness to balance out the hops here, as Im having a really hard time tasting anything but bitter nuts, grapefruit, and a bit of pine.

Hazy orange/amber with a fluffy,white, short-lived head. Nose is somewhat musty, quite bitter, with a good deal of grapefruit. Quite sweet--very nice, with some tobacco, pine resin, almonds. Excellent, pillowy mouthfeel.
Clear copper with a smallish white head. Sweet nose with orange, pine resin, grapefruit, caramel. Rather light flavor; musty, dry, bitter.

Fairly sweet nose, with touches of vanilla, maple syrup, walnuts. A bit of grassy hops. Clear copper with a good-sized white head. Flavor is somewhat light, but very nice. Slightly sweet, biscuity, with a dry bitterness. Not quite the melanoid goodness of the best o-fests, but fine nonetheless.
Black, more or less opaque, with a big, but short-lived light brown head. Lightly sweet nose, touch of molasses, some metallic notes. Dry, musty flavor, a hint of  sulphur, surprisingly boring.
beer_name: Arcadia Cocoa Loco Triple Chocolate Stout

review_blob: UPDATED: OCT 1, 2007

Light straw color, fairly hazy, small white head. Aroma is somewhat light, lemony tart, with some clove and banana. Flavor is really on point for the style--nice doses of cloves, banana, and bubblegum, with the banana winning in the end. Nicely tart, but not overpoweringly so. Possibly my favorite wit this summer.

Dark brown, mostly clear, with nearly no head. Nice, subtle nose--sweet, with hints of tobacco and raisins, slight bitterness. Flavor is relatively sweet, toffee-like, with some tobacco, leather, almonds and walnuts. Just a very light hint of some spices--anise or cardamom perhaps.

Clear, golden, with a decent-sized white head. Funky nose, rather bitter, with some off notes, maybe diacetyl, somewhat sweet. 
Gurf. Not pleasant flavor--really unpleasant vegetal notes, quite bitter, barely sweet at all, and, surprisingly, some alcohol heat. A minor disaster.

Hazy brown/amber with a very small head. Delicate aroma with a good bit of honey, some tobacco and cherry notes. Flavor is quite sweet, with much of the character of a nicely aged English barleywine--tobacco, walnuts, honey, cherry. Good dry bitterness finishes it off. Surprisingly impressive.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: Very cloudy orange/brown, with a huge head. Tons of yeast. Nose is grassy, slightly soapy, with some banana notes. Quite a bit of lemony tartness hits the tongue first, giving way powerful hop flavors--bitter, with some fresh cut grass. Perhaps too bitter, really. A very earthy quality underneath, and some sweetness--hints of the banana and bubblegum expected from a weizen, but not really enough residual sweetness to stand up to that hop blast.

Dark brown/clear black, with a short-lived tan head. Oddly light nose, a bit roasty, hint of soy, touch of red wine. Flavor is medium sweet, with a good bit of roasted malt, some chocolate notes. Alcohol is very well-hidden.

Good enough as tropico-lager goes. Was lucky to get one that wasnt skunked, and I could detect a decent noble hop aroma. Flavor was very light, somewhat fruity, nothing really off, but nothing to write home about. Very light hop profile.
